# Brand guidelines master document

## What this generates

Your comprehensive Brand Guidelines Master Document using Modular Brand Architecture Framework and Living Brand Guideline principles. You'll get three versions: Internal (40-60 pages with complete positioning, messaging, voice, visual identity, and governance), External (25-35 pages for partners with essential brand elements), and Quick-Reference (8-12 pages for at-a-glance guidance). This compiles all 16 foundational artifacts into one cohesive, actionable source of truth.

## Why you need this

Without a master brand guidelines document, your team has scattered knowledge in 16 different docs that nobody reads or follows consistently. Sales uses off-brand language. Design creates logo variations that violate standards. Partners butcher your messaging. A comprehensive, well-organized guideline document turns your brand foundation into an operational system—one place where everyone can find the answer to "how should this look, sound, or be positioned?"

## Before you start

This prompt works best when you've already completed the 16 foundational artifacts:
1. Target Customer Profiles
2. Market & Competitive Analysis  
3. Mission, Vision, Values & Brand Narrative
4. Brand Voice & Tone
5. Brand Personality & Archetype
6. Unique Value Propositions
7. Brand Positioning Statement
8. Brand Promise
9. Core Messaging Pillars
10. Message Map
11. Elevator Pitch & Boilerplate
12. Example Communications
13. Taglines & Slogans
14. Sales Methodology
15. Industry Context
16. Product/Service Catalog

You'll also need visual identity assets (logo, colors, typography) to include in the guidelines. If you don't have these yet, you can build the strategic/messaging sections now and add visual identity later.

## Prepare your inputs

Fill out this form before running the prompt. This is essentially gathering everything you've created so far.

### Foundation documents

**{{foundationDocs}}**  
All completed brand foundation documents from artifacts 1-16. You can either upload/paste the complete documents or provide summaries with key takeaways.

Include:
- Target Customer Profiles
- Market & Competitive Analysis
- Mission, Vision, Values & Brand Narrative
- Brand Voice & Tone guidelines
- Brand Personality & Archetype
- Unique Value Propositions
- Brand Positioning Statement
- Brand Promise
- Core Messaging Pillars
- Message Map
- Elevator Pitch & Boilerplate
- Example Communications (your swipe file)
- Taglines & Slogans
- Sales Methodology (if applicable)
- Industry Context
- Product/Service Catalog

### Visual identity assets

**{{visualAssets}}**  
Your visual brand elements including:
- Logo files (primary, secondary, icon variations)
- Color specifications (hex codes, RGB, CMYK, Pantone)
- Typography choices (font names, weights, usage rules)
- Photography style examples or guidelines
- Iconography system (if you have one)
- Any existing design standards or templates

If you don't have all visual assets finalized, note what you have and what's in development.

### Organizational context

**{{accessPermissions}}**  
Define who should have access to which versions of the guidelines.

Examples:
- **Internal full access:** All marketing, sales, product, and customer success teams
- **External version:** Agency partners, freelance designers, co-marketing partners
- **Quick-reference:** Everyone in the company, especially those who don't touch brand daily (engineering, finance, legal)

**{{existingTemplates}}**  
Any current templates you want incorporated or referenced.

Examples: PowerPoint template, Word letterhead, Email signature format, Social media post templates, Sales one-pager template, Case study template

**{{consistencyChallenges}}**  
Known pain points or areas where brand guidelines have been inconsistently applied in the past.

Examples:
- "Sales team uses generic value props instead of our messaging pillars"
- "Regional offices use old logo versions"
- "Social media tone varies wildly by channel"
- "Partners create co-branded materials that violate our visual standards"
- "Product team launches features without checking brand positioning"

**Pro tip:** The "consistency challenges" section is critical—it tells the LLM where to add extra emphasis, examples, and guardrails in the guidelines. Don't skip this.

## The prompt

Copy everything below this line and paste it into your LLM. Fill in your prepared inputs where indicated.

---
```
You are an expert brand strategist and documentation specialist tasked with creating a comprehensive Brand Guidelines Master Document that will serve as the definitive source of truth for all brand communications and applications.

## Your mission

Create a modular, professionally structured Brand Guidelines document that compiles all foundational brand elements into a cohesive, actionable resource. This document should follow industry-standard best practices from leading brand agencies (Pentagram, Wolff Olins, Siegel+Gale) while remaining flexible for future updates and scalable for organizational growth.

## Framework approach

Apply a Modular Brand Architecture Framework combined with Living Brand Guideline principles to create:
- Distinct, standalone modules that can be updated independently
- Clear navigation and logical information hierarchy
- Version control and governance protocols
- Scalable structure for team-specific distribution

## Document structure & deliverables

Create three distinct versions:

### 1. Internal version (40-60 pages)

Complete comprehensive guide including:
- Detailed table of contents with hierarchical navigation
- Full positioning and strategy rationale
- Complete messaging architecture with usage contexts
- Voice & tone guidelines with detailed examples
- Visual identity system with technical specifications
- Governance protocols and approval workflows
- Brand stewardship responsibilities
- Update request and review procedures

### 2. External version (25-35 pages)

Partner-facing guide including:
- Executive summary of brand essence
- Core messaging pillars and key narratives
- Essential voice & tone guidelines
- Visual identity usage rules and restrictions
- Approved asset library access
- Co-branding protocols (if applicable)
- Contact information for brand questions

### 3. Quick-reference version (8-12 pages)

One-sheet style guide including:
- Brand positioning statement
- Top 5 messaging pillars
- Voice & tone at-a-glance
- Logo usage do's and don'ts
- Color palette and typography essentials
- Key contact information

## Content requirements for each section

### Table of contents
- Logical hierarchical structure
- Page number references
- Section color-coding for easy navigation
- Quick-jump index for frequently referenced items

### Section templates (standardized format)

For each brand component, include:

**1. Brand positioning & strategy**
- Brand purpose, vision, mission
- Target audience definitions
- Competitive positioning
- Brand personality and archetype

**2. Messaging architecture**
- Value proposition
- Messaging pillars (3-5 core themes)
- Key messages by audience segment
- Proof points and supporting evidence
- Elevator pitch variations

**3. Voice & tone guidelines**
- Brand voice attributes with definitions
- Tone variation matrix by context/channel
- Language do's and don'ts
- Example phrases and communications
- Industry jargon guidance

**4. Visual identity system**
- Logo variations and usage rules
- Color palette (primary, secondary, tertiary)
- Typography specifications
- Photography/illustration style
- Iconography and graphic elements
- Layout principles and grid systems

**5. Application examples**
- Digital applications (website, social, email)
- Print applications (business cards, letterhead, brochures)
- Environmental applications (signage, trade show)
- Product/packaging applications (if applicable)

**6. Digital & social media guidelines**
- Channel-specific adaptations
- Profile setup standards
- Content formatting rules
- Hashtag strategy
- Response templates

## Governance & maintenance protocol

Include detailed documentation of:

**Brand ownership structure**
- Primary brand steward/owner (role and name)
- Department responsibilities
- Cross-functional brand council members

**Update workflow**
- How to request guideline updates
- Approval chain and decision-making authority
- Timeline for review and implementation
- Version control numbering system

**Review schedule**
- Annual comprehensive review date
- Quarterly spot-check protocols
- Trigger events requiring immediate review

**Compliance monitoring**
- Brand audit frequency and methodology
- Violation reporting process
- Education and training requirements

## Formatting & design specifications

- **Balance:** 60% written content, 40% visual examples
- **Accessibility:** Minimum 11pt font, high contrast, clear headings
- **Navigation:** Clickable table of contents, section dividers, page footers with section names
- **Visuals:** High-quality examples showing correct AND incorrect applications
- **Clarity:** Executive summaries at the start of each major section

## Output format

Deliver the guidelines as:
- Structured markdown document showing all content and hierarchy
- Annotations indicating where visual assets should be placed
- Clear labeling of which content appears in which version (Internal/External/Quick-Ref)
- Separate governance and maintenance appendix

## Quality checklist

Before finalizing, ensure:
- All foundation documents are accurately integrated
- Consistent terminology throughout all sections
- Clear rationale provided for brand decisions
- Practical examples accompany every rule
- Both aspirational and practical guidance included
- Contact information and escalation paths are current
- Version control information is prominent

## Client context

[Paste all your prepared inputs here]

### Foundation documents
{{foundationDocs}}

### Visual identity assets
{{visualAssets}}

### Organizational context
- Access permissions: {{accessPermissions}}
- Existing templates: {{existingTemplates}}
- Consistency challenges: {{consistencyChallenges}}
```

